post_text:
A good rule of thumb:
You know your child. If they have allergies, or other symptoms that match COVID but do not feel run down or sick, they should be okay. If you feel like they are getting sick and their symptom cannot be defined by something you already know they have, they need to stay home. If your child has a temperature above 100.4, they need to stay home. We will all need to do our part to stay in person this year. Thank you for your support.

post_text: IMPORTANT Update 4/27/20: Swink School District will be implementing a phased ending to the current school year. May 7th will be the last day for new assignments. After May 7th students who have finished their work or are content with their final grade at that point will be finished. Teachers will continue to work with students for the remaining two weeks to complete or improve upon unfinished work. We will have a check out schedule similar to the pick up schedule used in March. Checking out will take more time so the schedule will be spread over several days. We will begin checking out students who have completed their work starting on the 11th of May. A more detailed check out schedule and procedure will be posted soon. Thank you for your cooperation and patience as we continue to work together to make the process of ending the school year under the current “ Safer at Home” guidelines as painless as possible. Meal service will continue through the original end date of May 21st. (Please share to spread the word)

post_text: Update 4/21/20: Governor Polis announced today that regular face to face instruction has been suspended for the remainder of the school year. Swink School District will continue with the current remote learning plan. Schools were given a waiver on instructional time requirements for this school year. Those waivers required that schools continue remote learning through the end of their original school calendar. This recent announcement does not change our remote learning plans. Plans for ending the school year and returning materials will be coming soon.

post_text:
Swink School Update 3-19-2020

Since the last update was posted Governor Polis has issued an executive order that extends the break until April 17. This executive order does not affect our basic plan. We will plan to roll out remote learning for all students starting on March 30th. Remote learning will be in effect until at least April 17th. Continue to check the web page and school Facebook for updates.

During the next week we will be investigating the interest and feasibility of continuing school meal service. This would most likely be a take out option. Look for more information soon.

Superintendent
Kyle Hebberd

post_text:
Swink School Update

After a meeting with area Superintendents and county health officials a decision has been made to extend the break for students for another two weeks. All extracurricular activities at all levels will be suspended during this time. Prom will be postponed to a later date to be determined. Starting next week staff will work to build upon the remote learning plan released to parents prior to Spring Break. Please monitor your email and visit the Corona Update page on our web site or see the school facebook page for updates.

Superintendent
Kyle Hebberd

Swink School Kindergarten Round Up

-Thursday, April 4th

Parents, please call (719) 384-8103 to schedule an appointment.

Potential students must be 5 years old BEFORE July 1 to start Kindergarten in the Fall. Testing will take about an hour and a half.

Parents need to bring their child and the child’s birth certificate, immunization record and social security card. Please do not bring younger children, as childcare is not available.
